<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="129" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="129">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="129">
This is the first record of 
<taxonomicName authority="Bernhauer, 1902" authorityName="Bernhauer" authorityYear="1902" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Parocyusa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Parocyusa americana" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="129" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="americana">Parocyusa americana</taxonomicName>
since its description based on a female specimen collected from Peekskill, New York (
<bibRefCitation author="Casey, TL" journalOrPublisher="Transactions of the Academy of Science of St Louis" pageId="43" pageNumber="162" pagination="125 - 434" title="Observations on the staphylinid groups Aleocharinae and Xantholinini, chiefly of America." volume="16" year="1906">Casey 1906</bibRefCitation>
). This species is easily recognized to genus by its habitus and the only other known Nearctic species (
<taxonomicName authority="Bernhauer, 1902" authorityName="Bernhauer" authorityYear="1902" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Parocyusa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Parocyusa fuliginosa" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="129" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fuliginosa">Parocyusa fuliginosa</taxonomicName>
(Casey)) is darker, with a slightly shorter and more densely punctate pronotum, and has quadrate to slightly transverse antennomeres 8-10 (see Fig. 28 in 
<bibRefCitation author="Klimaszewski, J" journalOrPublisher="Pensoft Publishers, Sofia, Moscow" pageId="44" pageNumber="163" title="Aleocharine beetles (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae) of the province of Newfoundland and Labrador, Canada." year="2011">Klimaszewski et al. 2011</bibRefCitation>
). To promote nomenclatural stability, we designate a lectotype for 
<taxonomicName authority="Bernhauer, 1902" authorityName="Bernhauer" authorityYear="1902" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Parocyusa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Parocyusa americana" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="129" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="americana">Parocyusa americana</taxonomicName>
here.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="129">
Specimens of 
<taxonomicName authority="Bernhauer, 1902" authorityName="Bernhauer" authorityYear="1902" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Parocyusa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Parocyusa americana" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="129" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="americana">Parocyusa americana</taxonomicName>
were found on a stream bank and in a dry streambed under a rock. We expect 
<taxonomicName authority="Bernhauer, 1902" authorityName="Bernhauer" authorityYear="1902" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Parocyusa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Parocyusa americana" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="129" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="americana">Parocyusa americana</taxonomicName>
to occur broadly over northeastern North America in habitats near running water.
</paragraph>
